{"title_page": "National Association For Continence", "text_new": "\n\n'''National Association For Continence (NAFC)''' is a national, private, non-profit organization dedicated to improving the quality of life of people with incontinence, voiding dysfunction, and related pelvic floor disorders. NAFC's purpose is to be the leading source for public education and advocacy about the causes, prevention, diagnosis, treatments, and management alternatives for incontinence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nafc.org/ |title=Home &#124; Incontinence, Nocturia, Enlarged Prostate, and Prolapse Information |publisher=Nafc.org |date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthfinder.gov/orgs/HR2326.htm |title=National Association For Continence&nbsp;\u2013 healthfinder.gov&nbsp;\u2013 NAFC |publisher=healthfinder.gov |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Objectives ==\nNAFC's objectives are to destigmatize [[wiktionary:incontinence|incontinence]], to promote preventive measures, to motivate individuals to seek treatment, and to provide collaborative advocacy and service for those who are affected by this problem. To achieve its objectives, NAFC offers publications and services, such as: brochures detailing what every woman and man should know about bladder and bowel control, disease-specific booklets on [[multiple sclerosis]], [[spinal cord injury]], and [[Parkinson's disease]], [[Pelvic Muscle Exercise]] kits for men and women, Quality Care e-newsletter made up of articles written by leading professionals in the field, and a live webinar (online seminar) series that brings bladder and bowel health experts right to you. The National Association For Continence is supported by consumers/patients, health professionals, and industry.\n\n== Publications ==\nNAFC has a series of educational pamphlets and leaflets that are available to the public on various bladder and bowel health topics:\n\nGeneral Audience: [[Bladder retraining]], Urinary [[Catheterization]] of Men and Women, Fecal Incontinence, Incontinence and Odor Control, [[Overactive bladder]]\n\nFor Women: Incontinence and Childbirth, [[Pelvic organ prolapse]], Surgical Treatment for Female [[stress urinary incontinence]], Non-Surgical Treatment for Female [[stress urinary incontinence]] (includes instructions for Pelvic Muscle Exercises)\n\nFor Men: [[Male stress incontinence]], [[enlarged prostate]], Incontinence: What Every Man Should Know (includes instructions for Pelvic Muscle Exercises)\n\nNAFC also publishes the \"Resource Guide&nbsp;\u2013 A comprehensive directory of products and services for bladder and bowel control\" and its companion booklet, \"DISCOVERIES.\"\n\n== Membership ==\nConsumers and patients can help support NAFC through Donations. Health Professionals can become members of NAFC to receive various membership benefits, including being listed in NAFC's Find An Expert database. Read more about membership benefits on NAFC's website.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.nafc.org/ http://nafc.org/]\n\n\n[[Category:Incontinence]]\n[[Category:Disability organizations based in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''National Association For Continence (NAFC)''' is a national, private, non-profit organization dedicated to improving the quality of life of people with incontinence, voiding dysfunction, and related pelvic floor disorders. NAFC's purpose is to be the leading source for public education and advocacy about the causes, prevention, diagnosis, treatments, and management alternatives for incontinence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nafc.org/ |title=Home &#124; Incontinence, Nocturia, Enlarged Prostate, and Prolapse Information |publisher=Nafc.org |date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthfinder.gov/orgs/HR2326.htm |title=National Association For Continence&nbsp;\u2013 healthfinder.gov&nbsp;\u2013 NAFC |publisher=healthfinder.gov |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Objectives ==\nNAFC's objectives are to destigmatize [[wiktionary:incontinence|incontinence]], to promote preventive measures, to motivate individuals to seek treatment, and to provide collaborative advocacy and service for those who are affected by this problem. To achieve its objectives, NAFC offers publications and services, such as: brochures detailing what every woman and man should know about bladder and bowel control, disease-specific booklets on [[multiple sclerosis]], [[spinal cord injury]], and [[Parkinson's disease]], [[Pelvic Muscle Exercise]] kits for men and women, Quality Care e-newsletter made up of articles written by leading professionals in the field, and a live webinar (online seminar) series that brings bladder and bowel health experts right to you. The National Association For Continence is supported by consumers/patients, health professionals, and industry.\n\n== Publications ==\nNAFC has a series of educational pamphlets and leaflets that are available to the public on various bladder and bowel health topics:\n\nGeneral Audience: [[Bladder retraining]], Urinary [[Catheterization]] of Men and Women, Fecal Incontinence, Incontinence and Odor Control, [[Overactive bladder]]\n\nFor Women: Incontinence and Childbirth, [[Pelvic organ prolapse]], Surgical Treatment for Female [[stress urinary incontinence]], Non-Surgical Treatment for Female [[stress urinary incontinence]] (includes instructions for Pelvic Muscle Exercises)\n\nFor Men: [[Male stress incontinence]], [[enlarged prostate]], Incontinence: What Every Man Should Know (includes instructions for Pelvic Muscle Exercises)\n\nNAFC also publishes the \"Resource Guide&nbsp;\u2013 A comprehensive directory of products and services for bladder and bowel control\" and its companion booklet, \"DISCOVERIES.\"\n\n== Membership ==\nConsumers and patients can help support NAFC through Donations. Health Professionals can become members of NAFC to receive various membership benefits, including being listed in NAFC's Find An Expert database. Read more about membership benefits on NAFC's website.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.nafc.org/\n\n\n[[Category:Incontinence]]\n[[Category:Disability organizations based in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "AvlAeroflow", "label": "safe", "comment": "The NAFC website does not have www.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Association_For_Continence"}
{"title_page": "Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale", "text_new": "{{short description|Snack company}}\n'''Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale''' is an Indian snacks enterprise which popularly runs in [[Maharashtra]]. It was formed by Shri. Raghunath Rao Chitale in 1950 as a subsidiary of the Chitale Group of Industries. Its first outlet was set up in Bajirao Road, Pune City. Although its outlets are limited to major cities of Maharashtra, the products are distributed all across India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chitalegroup.com/chitale-group-companies/about-chitale-bandhu|title=Chitale Bandhu - Sweets, Mithais, Namkeen, Instant Mixes, snacks, Bajirao road, Deccan Gymkhana, Pune, Maharashtra, India.|website=Chitale Groups|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/bhakarwadi-a-beloved-maharashtrian-snack-that-originated-in-gujarat-1726625|title=Bhakarwadi: A Popular Snack You Believe is Maharashtrian Actually Belongs to Gujarat|website=NDTV Food|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Over the years, Chitale Bandhu has been known for making [[Namkeen (food)|namkeen]] (especially [[bakarwadi]]s) and sweets. It is also known to export its namkeen to countries such asU.S., Singapore, and Israel.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/variety/punes-vendor-of-sweets/article23029571.ece|title=Pune\u2019s vendor of sweets|last=Iyer|first=Satyanarayan|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> The brand menu consists of over sixty different kinds of sweets and forty different kinds of namkeen. The enterprise has an average turnover of around 200 crore [[rupee]]s with around 2,000 to 2,500 customers shopping every day.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nIn mid-1930s, Bhaskar Ganesh Chitale, also known as B. G. Chitale, was an ordinary milk businessman located in a small village of Limb Gaon situated in the [[Satara district|Satara]] district of Maharashtra. Due to an unexpected turn of events, his cattle fell prey to an unknown disease resulting in their death. This caused a major loss in the business owned by the Chitale Family.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://indiasuccessstories.com/view_story/Evolution-of-Chitale-Bhandhu-Sweet-Mart-|title=Evolution of Chitale Bhandhu Sweet Mart|last=Chitale|first=Shrikrishna|website=India Success Stories|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> In 1939, with a fresh start B. G. Chitale founded the Chitale Group of industries by starting their first enterprise, Chitale Dairy. The brand quickly gained reputation for its quality after it expanded its reach after Raghunath Rao Chitale (Also known as Bhau Chitale; Son of B. G. Chitale) set up a shop in [[Mumbai|Mumbai, Maharashtra]] in a partnership.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the year 1946, the partnership came to an end and Raghunath Rao Chitale had to leave Mumbai. He then moved to Pune and started vending milk supplied to him from [[Bhiwandi]]. The business became a success in the city and in the year 1950 he bought a 500 [[Square foot|square feet]] shop where he set up a new enterprise, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The shop is still operational and is now considered the headquarters of Chitale Bandhu.\n\n=== Introduction to Bakarwadi ===\nChitale Bandhu started the sale of [[bakarwadi]] in 1970. Due to the growth of demand, the enterprise then installed machines to maintain the original shape and size of the bakarwadi.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early nineties, the bhakarwadi sale was around {{cvt|300|kg}} a day.<ref name=\":0\" /> Currently, the enterprise sells about {{cvt|3000|kg}} of the snack daily. Introduction of bakarwadi in Chitale Bandhu's shop increased the sales of the enterprise to a great extent.<ref name=\":2\" /> This growing demand for the new snack was fulfilled after B. G. Chitale's toured Japan in the 1970s. With the new innovations and technology, the enterprise adopted a semi-automatic production of bakarwadi in 1989.<ref name=\":2\" /> Later, the production was made completely automatic. This allowed the enterprise to grow faster. In the following years Chitale Bandhu started opening multiple branches around the city of Pune.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Computerized billing system ===\nIn 1985, the enterprise installed a computerized billing system.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Products ==\n\n=== Snacks and namkeen ===\nChitale Bandhu Mithaiwale has over 40 varieties of Namkeen sold at multiple outlets. Some of the common and widely sold Namkeen include: [[bakarwadi]], various [[Bombay mix|Chivda]], [[Farsan (food)|Farsan]], Gathi, Papadi, various [[Sev (food)|sev]], and [[Shankarpali]]. Along with these there are also multiple [[chaat]] products such as [[Samosa]] and [[Kachori]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flavorsofmycity.com/chitale-bandhu-mithaiwale|title=Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale - Pune (MH) - Shop By Cities :Flavors of My City|website=www.flavorsofmycity.com|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dineout.co.in/pune/chitale-bandhu-mithaiwale-deccan-gymkhana-west-pune-15688/menu|title=Menu of Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale, Deccan Gymkhana, Pune {{!}} Dineout discovery|website=www.dineout.co.in|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==== Bakarwadi ====\nChitale Bandhu has been known for selling [[bakarwadi]] since the early 1970s. Although this snack was originally made in [[Gujarat]], it gained popularity in Maharashtra when it was introduced (Many believe that this is due to its spice which is common in Maharashtra).<ref name=\":2\" /> Many sources, such as NDTV foods, believe that although the enterprise was performing well in the sweets sector, after the introduction of [[bakarwadi]] in the menu, its sales increased rapidly. NDTV foods also referred to this snack as a \"bronzed snack\".<ref name=\":2\" /> With the technological change, the organisation made the production of bakarwadi automatic, which allowed it to boost the production of bakarwadi. This increased the sale of bakarwadis from 300 kilos a day in 1970, to over 3000 kilos a day in 2012.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Sev ====\nA large variety of [[Sev (food)|sev]] is available at Chitale Bandhu, such as:\n\n* Tikhat Jad (spicy and thick) Sev \n* Sadhi (Normal-sized) Sev\n* Zero-sized Sev\n* Masala Sev\n* Palak (Spinach) Sev\n* Tomato Sev\n\n==== Chivda ====\nThe enterprise has also been known for selling variety of [[Bombay mix|chivda]], such as:\n\n* [[Flattened rice|Poha]] (Flattened rice) Chivda\n* Maka (Corn) Chivda\n* Potato Chivda\n* Namkeen Mix\n\n=== Sweets ===\nThere are over 60 different sweets on the menu of the enterprise. The popular sweets that are sold include: various types of [[halva]] (such as almond and pineapple flavour), [[Barfi|burfi]], sweet rolls, [[peda]], [[Laddu]] and [[Jalebi]] (also pronounced as \"Jilebi\" ).<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==== Burfi ====\nA list of burfi which are sold at Chitale Bandhu include:\n\n* [[Kaju katli|Kaju Katali]]\n* Anjir ([[Common fig|Fig]]) Burfi\n* Pista Burfi\n* Malai Burfi\n\n==== Rolls (sweet) ====\nThe enterprise has various flavours of roll which include: [[gulkand]], mango, anjir, and cashew-apple.\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nIn 2017, the workers of Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale, went on a strike who demanded a hike in their salaries. Following the labor court's order, the workers returned back to work on October 1, 2017.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/pune/civic/chitale-workers-say-they-were-harassed/articleshow/60945588.cms|title=Chitale workers say they were harassed|last=Kulkarni|first=Prachee KulkarniPrachee|last2=Oct 5|first2=Pune Mirror {{!}} Updated:|website=Pune Mirror|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16|last3=2017|last4=Ist|first4=02:30}}</ref> However, according to the workers, they were not given a professional treatment after re-joining. Many of them stated that they were made to sit idle in the working hours. One of the employee, Vandana Ughade, claimed that the doors of the workplace were also closed to confine the workers in.<ref name=\":4\" /> Indraneel Chitale, the owner of the enterprise in 2017, countered all the claims by stating that the workers were left idle because the production itself was low due to the preceding strike.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Snack company}}\n'''Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale''' is an Indian snacks enterprise which popularly runs in [[Maharashtra]]. It was formed by Shri. Raghunath Rao Chitale in 1950 as a subsidiary of the Chitale Group of Industries. Its first outlet was set up in Bajirao Road, Pune City. Although its outlets are limited to major cities of Maharashtra, the products are distributed all across India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chitalegroup.com/chitale-group-companies/about-chitale-bandhu|title=Chitale Bandhu - Sweets, Mithais, Namkeen, Instant Mixes, snacks, Bajirao road, Deccan Gymkhana, Pune, Maharashtra, India.|website=Chitale Groups|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/bhakarwadi-a-beloved-maharashtrian-snack-that-originated-in-gujarat-1726625|title=Bhakarwadi: A Popular Snack You Believe is Maharashtrian Actually Belongs to Gujarat|website=NDTV Food|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Over the years, Chitale Bandhu has been known for making [[Namkeen (food)|namkeen]] (especially [[Bakarwadi|bakarwadis]]) and sweets. It is also known to export its namkeen to countries such asU.S., Singapore, and Israel.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/variety/punes-vendor-of-sweets/article23029571.ece|title=Pune\u2019s vendor of sweets|last=Iyer|first=Satyanarayan|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> The brand menu consists of over sixty different kinds of sweets and forty different kinds of namkeen. The enterprise has an average turnover of around 200 crore [[Rupee|rupees]] with around 2,000 to 2,500 customers shopping every day.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== History ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nIn mid-1930s, Bhaskar Ganesh Chitale, also known as B. G. Chitale, was an ordinary milk businessman located in a small village of Limb Gaon situated in the [[Satara district|Satara]] district of Maharashtra. Due to an unexpected turn of events, his cattle fell prey to an unknown disease resulting in their death. This caused a major loss in the business owned by the Chitale Family.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://indiasuccessstories.com/view_story/Evolution-of-Chitale-Bhandhu-Sweet-Mart-|title=Evolution of Chitale Bhandhu Sweet Mart|last=Chitale|first=Shrikrishna|website=India Success Stories|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> In 1939, with a fresh start B. G. Chitale founded the Chitale Group of industries by starting their first enterprise, Chitale Dairy. The brand quickly gained reputation for its quality after it expanded its reach after Raghunath Rao Chitale (Also known as Bhau Chitale; Son of B. G. Chitale) set up a shop in [[Mumbai|Mumbai, Maharashtra]] in a partnership.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the year 1946, the partnership came to an end and Raghunath Rao Chitale had to leave Mumbai. He then moved to Pune and started vending milk supplied to him from [[Bhiwandi]]. The business became a success in the city and in the year 1950 he bought a 500 [[Square foot|square feet]] shop where he set up a new enterprise, Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The shop is still operational and is now considered the headquarters of Chitale Bandhu.\n\n=== Introduction to Bakarwadi ===\nChitale Bandhu started the sale of [[bakarwadi]] in 1970. Due to the growth of demand, the enterprise then installed machines to maintain the original shape and size of the bakarwadi.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early nineties, the bhakarwadi sale was around {{cvt|300|kg}} a day.<ref name=\":0\" /> Currently, the enterprise sells about {{cvt|3000|kg}} of the snack daily. Introduction of bakarwadi in Chitale Bandhu's shop increased the sales of the enterprise to a great extent.<ref name=\":2\" /> This growing demand for the new snack was fulfilled after B. G. Chitale's toured Japan in the 1970s. With the new innovations and technology, the enterprise adopted a semi-automatic production of bakarwadi in 1989.<ref name=\":2\" /> Later, the production was made completely automatic. This allowed the enterprise to grow faster. In the following years Chitale Bandhu started opening multiple branches around the city of Pune.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Computerized billing system ===\nIn 1985, the enterprise installed a computerized billing system.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Products ==\n\n=== Snacks and namkeen ===\nChitale Bandhu Mithaiwale has over 40 varieties of Namkeen sold at multiple outlets. Some of the common and widely sold Namkeen include: [[bakarwadi]], various [[Bombay mix|Chivda]], [[Farsan (food)|Farsan]], Gathi, Papadi, various [[Sev (food)|sev]], and [[Shankarpali]]. Along with these there are also multiple [[chaat]] products such as [[Samosa]] and [[Kachori]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flavorsofmycity.com/chitale-bandhu-mithaiwale|title=Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale - Pune (MH) - Shop By Cities :Flavors of My City|website=www.flavorsofmycity.com|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dineout.co.in/pune/chitale-bandhu-mithaiwale-deccan-gymkhana-west-pune-15688/menu|title=Menu of Chitale Bandhu Mithaiwale, Deccan Gymkhana, Pune {{!}} Dineout discovery|website=www.dineout.co.in|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==== Bakarwadi ====\nChitale Bandhu has been known for selling [[bakarwadi]] since the early 1970s. Although this snack was originally made in [[Gujarat